'''Mark Mendelevich Persits''' ({{lang-ru|Марк Менделевич Персиц}}, ~ 1908–1986) was a Soviet propagandist of atheism and a scientific worker in the study of problems of religion and atheism, Writer, historian of social thought<ref>[http://relstud-hist.spbu.ru/articles/persic-mark-mendelevic Персиц Марк Менделевич]</ref>.

Persits was an employee of the [[:ru:Институт истории АН СССР|Institute of History of the USSR Academy of Sciences]]. In 1952 he defended his thesis for the degree of candidate of historical sciences on the topic «[[Decree on separation of church from state and school from church|Decree of the Council of People's Commissars of the RSFSR of January 23 (February 5), 1918 "On the separation of church from state and school from the church"]] and its historical significance».

He studied the history of Marxist atheism and atheism and the history of free thinking and the struggle for freedom of conscience in Russia<ref>[http://relstud-hist.spbu.ru/articles/persic-mark-mendelevic Персиц Марк Менделевич]</ref>. Persits suggested that the success of an atheist lecture depended not so much on the content as on the lecturer<ref>[https://books.google.ru/books?id=gTRFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA157&dq=Mark+Persits&hl=ru&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiD38rFs9_cAhXiDpoKHarmCAEQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=Mark%20Persits&f=false Victoria Smolkin. A Sacred Space Is Never Empty: A History of Soviet Atheism. / Princeton University Press, 2018 / p. 157]</ref>.
