{{For|the bishop of Nocera de' Pagani|Paolo Giovio (il Giovane)}} {{short description|16th-century Italian Catholic priest and physician, historian, and biographer}} {{Infobox Christian leader | type = Bishop | honorific-prefix = | name = Paolo Giovio | title = Bishop of Nocera de' Pagani | image = Paolo Giovio-portrait.gif | image_size = | alt = | caption = Paolo Giovio | church = [[Catholic Church]] | archdiocese = | diocese = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nocera Inferiore-Sarno|Diocese of Nocera de' Pagani]] | see = | term = 1528–1552 | predecessor = [[Domenico Giacobazzi]] | successor = [[Giulio Giovio]] <!-- Orders --> | ordination = | ordained_by = | consecration = 17 Apr 1533 | consecrated_by = [[Gabriele Mascioli Foschi]] | cardinal = | created_cardinal_by = | rank = <!-- Personal details --> | birth_date = 19 April 1483 | birth_place = [[Isola Comacina]] of [[Lake Como]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1552|12|11|1483|4|19|df=y}} | death_place = [[Florence]] | previous_post = | nationality = | religion = | ethnicity = }}
'''Paolo Giovio''' (also spelled ''Paulo Jovio''; [[Latin]]: ''Paulus Jovius''; 19 April 1483&nbsp;– 11 December 1552) was an [[Italy|Italian]] physician, historian, biographer, and prelate.
==Early life== Little is known about Giovio's youth. He was a native of [[Como]]; his family was from the [[Isola Comacina]] of [[Lake Como]]. His father, a [[notary]], died around 1500. He was educated under the direction of his elder brother [[Benedetto Giovio|Benedetto]], a humanist and historian. Although interested in literature, he was sent to [[Padua]] to study medicine. He graduated in 1511.
==Career== Giovio worked as physician in Como but, after the plague spread in that city he moved to [[Rome]], settling there in 1513. [[Pope Leo X]] assigned him a ''cathedra'' (chair) of [[Ethics|Moral Philosophy]] and, later, that of [[Natural philosophy|Natural Philosophy]] in the Roman university. He was also knighted by the Pope.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/08530b.htm|title=Paulus Jovius|work=[[Catholic Encyclopedia]]|last = Schlager|first = Patricius|volume = 8|location = New York|publisher = Robert Appleton Company|date = 12 July 2013|origyear = 1910}}</ref> In the same period he started to write historical essays. He wrote a [[memoir]] of Leo soon after his death.
In 1517 Giovio was appointed as the personal physician for Cardinal [[Giulio di Giuliano de' Medici]] (the future Pope Clement VII). In the field he wrote some treatises, like the ''De optima victus ratione'', in which he expresses his doubts about the current [[pharmacology]], and the need to improve prevention before the cure.
Giovio helped Clement VII during the 1527 [[sack of Rome (1527)|sack of Rome]]. From 1526 to 1528, he stayed on the island of [[Ischia]] as [[Vittoria Colonna]]'s guest.<ref>{{Cite book|year = 1995|title = Paolo Giovio: The Historian and the Crisis of Sixteenth-Century Italy|chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=sXrVSfSMu9gC|last = Zimmerman|first = T. C. Price|publisher = Princeton University Press|isbn = 9781400821839|chapter = Ischia, 1527-1528|pages = 86–105}}</ref> In 1528, he became [[bishop of Nocera de' Pagani]]. Giovio wrote an account of [[Dmitry Gerasimov]]'s embassy to Clement VII, which related detailed geographical data on [[Muscovy]].
In 1536 Giovio had a [[villa]] built for him on Lake Como, which he called ''Museo'', and which he used for his collection of portraits of famous people. After Clement's death, he retired. As well as paintings, he sought antiquities, etc., and his collection was one of the first to include pieces from the [[New World]]. A set of copies of the paintings from the collection, now known as the [[Giovio Series]], is on display in the [[Uffizi Gallery]].
==Death== In 1549 [[Pope Paul III]] denied Giovio the title of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Como|Bishop of Como]], and he moved to [[Florence]], where he died in 1552.
==Works== [[image:Francesco da Sangallo, monumento al Vescovo Paolo Giovio (1560) 1.JPG|thumb|Monument to Paolo Giovo by [[Francesco da Sangallo]], in [[San Lorenzo di Firenze|San Lorenzo]] Basilica, [[Florence]]]] Giovio is chiefly known as the author of a celebrated work of contemporary history, ''Historiarum sui temporis libri&nbsp;XLV'', of a collection of lives of famous men, ''Vitae virorum illustrium'' (1549‑57), and of ''Elogia virorum bellica virtute illustrium'', (Florence, 1554), which may be translated as ''Praise of Men Illustrious for Courage in War'' (1554). He is best remembered as a chronicler of the [[Italian Wars]]. His eyewitness accounts of many of the battles form one of the most significant primary sources for the period. Many pages of his work are devoted to [[Skanderbeg]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Comparative literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BJ1RAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=2 January 2014|year=1953|page=20}}</ref>
Giovio's notable work include: *''De romanis piscibus'' (1524) *''De legatione Basilii Magni Principis Moschoviae'' (1525) *''Commentario de le cose de’ Turchi'' (1531) *''[http://www.elfinspell.com/PaoloStartStyle.html Elogia virorum litteris illustrium]'' or ''Elogia doctorum virorum'' (1546) *''Descriptio Britanniae, Scotiae, Hyberniae et Orchadum'' (1548) *''Vitae'' (1549) *''[https://books.google.com/books?id=INJJ14l9qFUC&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''Pauli Jovii historiarum sui temporis]'' (1550–52) *''[[Elogia virorum bellica virtute illustrium]]'' (1554), as an eye witness of many people involved in the [[Italian Wars]] including [[Gonzalo Fernández de Córdoba]] *''[https://archive.org/details/impresemilitarie00giov Dialogo dell'imprese militari et amorose]'' (1555)
