[[File:Tedo Zhordania, Georgian historian.jpg|thumb|Tedo Zhordania]]

'''Tedo Zhordania''' ({{lang-ka|თედო ჟორდანია}}; 10 April 1854 – 22 October 1916) was a [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] historian, philologist, and educator.

Born in an Orthodox priest's family in the village of [[Mokvi]], then part of the [[Russian Empire]], Zhordania studied theology in [[Kutaisi]], [[Tbilisi]], and [[Moscow]]. The leading Russian historian of that period, [[Vasily Klyuchevsky]], recommended the young Georgian student to pursue his career in Moscow, but Zhordania returned to Tbilisi, where he taught geography at a theological college and supervised church schools. An amateur historian, Zhordania revealed, studied, and published a number of hitherto unknown historical records. Many of these sources were subsequently lost and are known to us exclusively from Zhordania's publications. He died in [[Kaspi]]. He was subsequently buried at the [[Didube Pantheon]] in Tbilisi.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Guntsadze|first1=Manuchar|last2=Turazashvili|first2=Natia|title=თედო ჟორდანიას თხზულებათა კრებულის პუბლიკაცია|journal=Georgian Studies|date=2012|volume=13–14|pages=244–245|url=http://georgianstudies.ge/docs/XIII%202010.pdf|trans-title=On Publication of the Collection of Works by Tedo Zhordania|language=Georgian, English|issn=1987-9563|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407081518/http://georgianstudies.ge/docs/XIII%202010.pdf|archivedate=2014-04-07|df=}}</ref>

